            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kai Mendoza is a product of San Francisco's fog and friction, born and raised in the Excelsior District. The son of a Filipino immigrant mother who worked as a nurse\u2019s aide and an Irish-American father who was a union electrician, Kai\u2019s upbringing was grounded in the tangible. Their small home echoed with the values of hard work and skilled hands. While his peers chased academic scholarships, Kai found his focus in the school\u2019s underfunded woodshop, feeling more at home with a set of calipers than a textbook.\n\nAfter high school, Kai felt adrift in a city that seemed to value code over craft. He worked a series of dead-end jobs until a guidance counselor from a community program pointed him toward a CNC Machining certification at City College. It was a revelation. The intersection of digital design and powerful, precise machinery clicked instantly. He discovered a talent for translating complex digital blueprints into flawless, physical components.\n\nHis career began at a small fabrication shop in the Bayview. His meticulous nature and intuitive problem-solving skills quickly set him apart. Now, as the Lead Fabrication Technician for a thriving prototyping firm in the Dogpatch, he\u2019s the crucial link between tech startups\u2019 ideas and their first physical products. He manages a small team, his days filled with the hum of machinery and the smell of cutting fluid\u2014a sensory reality he prefers to sterile office parks.\n\nHis 3.8-mile commute on the T Third light rail is a daily ritual, carrying him from the quiet residential streets of his youth to the city\u2019s industrial heart. He lives with his long-term partner, Lena, a graphic designer, in a rent-controlled apartment a few blocks from his childhood home. He maintains a deep connection to his widowed mother, visiting her weekly. Kai\u2019s dream isn\u2019t a disruptive startup, but a down payment on a small house in the Excelsior. He wants to own a piece of the city that shaped him, proving that the people who build San Francisco still have a place within it."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was sixteen, dust motes dancing in the slanted light of the school woodshop. After three failed attempts, the two pieces of pine finally slid together, forming a perfect dovetail joint. He ran a thumb over the impossibly flush seam, the scent of cut wood sharp in his nostrils. In that quiet, tactile click, he felt a rightness no report card had ever given him. It wasn't about being smart; it was about being capable. This feeling became the blueprint for the rest of his life.\n\n2.\nThe first time he ran a program at City College, the CNC machine roared to life with terrifying force. Kai flinched, but then watched, mesmerized, as the cutting head carved his digital design into a block of aluminum with inhuman precision. It wasn't replacing his hands; it was amplifying them. The thunderous noise quieted in his mind, replaced by a profound sense of discovery. He hadn't been obsolete, just speaking the wrong language. Now, he was fluent.\n\n3.\nIt was a memory of his father, kneeling before an open junction box in their hallway. He recalled not the danger, but the reverence. His dad\u2019s calloused hands moved with a practiced grace, confidently stripping and twisting wires, his face a mask of focus. He explained the flow of power with a simple clarity that made it feel like magic. Kai learned then that true value wasn't just in the finished product, but in the hands and knowledge that brought it into being.\n\n4.\nThe Bayview shop floor was thick with tension; a client\u2019s crucial prototype kept coming out with micro-fractures. After everyone else gave up, Kai stayed late. He ignored the specs and trusted his gut, making minute adjustments to the machine's speed and path based on sound and feel alone. The sixth piece emerged flawless. Holding the cool, perfect component under the stark workshop lights, he felt a quiet, unshakable confidence settle in his chest. He belonged there.\n\n5.\nHe stood with Lena on a quiet Sunday, the fog rolling down the hill, looking at a small house with peeling paint. \u201cThe morning light would be beautiful in that window,\u201d she said, tucking her arm through his. He didn't see the work it needed; he saw a future. He pictured his mom\u2019s garden in the back, a small workshop in the garage, and the two of them walking home. The dream wasn't abstract anymore; it had an address."
